```rust
pub fn wrap_impl_trait<'c, 'i, I: 'i, O: 'i>(
    f: impl Fn(&'i I) -> &'i O + 'c,
) -> impl Fn(&'i I) -> &'i O + 'c {
    f
}
pub struct Outer(Inner);
struct Inner;

impl Outer {
    fn field(&self) -> &Inner {
        &self.0
    }
}

impl Inner {
    fn hello_world<'r, R, N>(this: N)
    where
        N: Fn(&R) -> &Self,
    {
        println!("Hello, World!");
    }
}

pub fn foo(m: &Outer) {
    let n = wrap_impl_trait(Outer::field);
    Inner::hello_world(n);
}
```
```
error: implementation of `std::ops::FnOnce` is not general enough
  --> src/lib.rs:26:5
   |
26 |     Inner::hello_world(n);
   |     ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
   |
   = note: Due to a where-clause on `Inner::hello_world`,
   = note: `impl std::ops::Fn<(&Outer,)>` must implement `std::ops::FnOnce<(&Outer,)>`
   = note: but `impl std::ops::Fn<(&'0 Outer,)>` only implements `std::ops::FnOnce<(&Outer,)>` for the lifetime `'0`
```
[Playground](https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=beta&mode=debug&edition=2018&gist=7b721d819612b7673104e9153f4b8fa7)

Replacing wrap_impl_trait with the following works (Removing explicit `'i`)
```rust
pub fn wrap_impl_trait<'c, I, O>(
    f: impl Fn(& I) -> &O,
) -> impl Fn(& I) -> & O + 'c {
    f
}
```

Sometimes, explicitly annotating with `'i` is required, for example when chaining two closures.
